microstructure: Coarse grain with dendritic structure. Light regions are rich in W and darker regions are rich in Ti.
evidence: The C-3009, W1 and M1 alloys have coarse grain structures, with the average grain size over 1.5 mm (Fig. 2aec). A dendritic structure is clearly seen in the W-containing C-3009 and W1 (Fig. 2a and b). The light regions are rich in W and darker regions are rich in Hf (in C-3009) or Ti (in W1).

The multi-principal element alloys M4 and MW1 were considerably stronger showing s 0.2 values of 1100 MPa and 1440 MPa, respectively. In the M4 and MW1 alloys, deformation localized inside macroscopic shear bands, which caused cracking and fracture along these bands at true compression strains of ~0.25 and 0.11,  respectively, after achieving peak true stress values of 1757 MPa and 1900 MPa.

In the M4 and MW1 alloys, deformation localized inside macroscopic shear bands, which caused cracking and fracture along these bands at true compression strains of ~0.25 and 0.11,  respectively, after achieving peak true stress values of 1757 MPa and 1900 MPa.

A considerable loss in compressive ductility was observed in C-3009 at 1200 C. Visual observation of the tested C-3009 samples showed that this loss in compressive ductility was due to strain localization in a single ~45 -inclined shear band and fracturing along this band. Such behavior indicates deformation instability of C-3009 at 1200 C. Fine-grained structure and multiple cracks were observed inside this shear band.
